Release notes documentation:

Previously the Java Source Reformatter would reformat Java source does not treat try and synchronized blocks as blocks when it encounters them with control structures. So

```
if (foo == bar) try {
   baz();
} catch (Exception all) {
   log.(....);
}
```

was reformatted as :

```
if (foo == bar) {
  try {
    baz();
  } catch (Exception all) {
    log.(....);
  }
}
```
The additional added basic block layer is not needed as the try is already a block. The redundant braces are no longer added. The same applies for a synchronized block as well:

```
if (foo == bar) synchronized(quux) {
   baz();
}
```
was previously reformatted as :
```
if (foo == bar) {
  synchronized(quux) {
    baz();
  }
}
```
but will now be left alone.

In addition to "if/else" this formatting all affects other control structures such as "for", "for-each" and "while".

Manually adding braces around a try or synchronized is still allowed and the reformatter will leave them as-typed unless the source reformatter option for Java braces has been configured to "Eliminate".

@junichi11 we had a lot of discussion on public vs friend APIs about a year ago. There was little consensus aside from a recognition that we need to move towards stabilising and exposing necessary APIs.  These APIs may not be perfect, and perhaps we need a better in-development and deprecation mechanism, but IMO we should not be adding in friend access for third-party projects - that is just adding a stability issue by the back door.

I suggested @jGauravGupta propose a PR to expose what is required, and (I think) also start a mailing list thread on this.  With a move to quarterly releases we need to move away from plugin authors requiring either use of implementation versions or friend access.

Adding in a review request from @lkishalmi who started that earlier conversation on public vs friend.

